# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-segmentation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] An **air gap**, **air wall**, **air gapping** or **disconnected network** is a network security measure employed on one or more computers to ensure that a secure computer network is physically isolated from unsecured networks, such as the public Internet or an unsecured local area network.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] It means a computer or network has no network interface controllers connected to other networks, with a physical or conceptual air gap, analogous to the air gap used in plumbing to maintain water quality.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] An *air-gapped* computer or network is one that has no network interfaces, either wired or wireless, connected to outside networks.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] Many computers, even when they are not plugged into a wired network, have a wireless network interface controller (WiFi) and are connected to nearby wireless networks to access the Internet and update software.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] This represents a security vulnerability, so air-gapped computers have their wireless interface controller either permanently disabled or physically removed.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] To move data between the outside world and the air-gapped system, it is necessary to write data to a physical medium such as a thumbdrive, and physically move it between computers.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] It is easier to control than a direct full network interface, which can be attacked from an exterior insecure system and, if malware infects the secure system, can be used to export secure data.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] For this reason, some new hardware technologies are also available, like unidirectional data diodes or bidirectional diodes (also called electronic airgaps), which physically separate the network and transportation layers and copy and filter the application data.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] In environments where networks or devices are rated to handle different levels of classified information, the two disconnected devices or networks are referred to as *low side* and *high side*, *low* being unclassified and *high* referring to classified, or classified at a higher level.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] This is also occasionally referred to as *red* (classified) and *black* (unclassified).
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] Access policies are often based on the Bell–LaPadula confidentiality model, where data can be moved low-to-high with minimal security measures, while high-to-low requires much more stringent procedures to ensure protection of the data at a higher level of classification.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] In some cases (for instance, in industrial critical systems), the policy is different: data can be moved from high to low with minimal security measures, but moving from low to high requires a high level of procedural safeguards to ensure the integrity of the industrial safety system.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] The concept represents nearly the maximum protection one network can have from another (save turning the device off).
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] One way to transfer data between the outside world and the air-gapped system is to copy data on a removable storage medium such as a removable disk or USB flash drive and physically carry the storage to the other system.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] This access still has to be carefully controlled since a USB drive may have vulnerabilities (see below).
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] The upside to this is that such a network can generally be regarded as a closed system (in terms of information, signals, and emissions security), unable to be accessed from the outside world.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] This is the reason that another way to transfer data, used in appropriate situations like critical industries, is to use data diodes and electronic airgaps, which assure a physical cut of the network by a specific hardware.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] Sophisticated computer viruses for use in cyberwarfare, such as Stuxnet and Agent.BTZ have been designed to infect air-gapped systems by exploiting security holes related to the handling of removable media.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] The possibility of using acoustic communication has also been demonstrated by researchers.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] Researchers have also demonstrated the feasibility of data exfiltration using FM frequency signals.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] Limitations imposed on devices used in these environments may include a ban on wireless connections to or from the secure network, or similar restrictions on EM leakage from the secure network through the use of TEMPEST or a Faraday cage.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] Despite a lack of direct connection to other systems, air-gapped networks have been shown to be vulnerable to attack in various circumstances.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] Scientists in 2013 demonstrated the viability of air gap malware designed to defeat air gap isolation using acoustic signaling.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] Shortly after that, network security researcher Dragos Ruiu's BadBIOS received press attention.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] In 2014, researchers introduced *AirHopper*, a bifurcated attack pattern showing the feasibility of data exfiltration from an isolated computer to a nearby mobile phone, using FM frequency signals.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] In 2015, BitWhisper, a covert signaling channel between air-gapped computers using thermal manipulations, was introduced.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] BitWhisper supports bidirectional communication and requires no additional dedicated peripheral hardware.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] Later in 2015, researchers introduced GSMem, a method for exfiltrating data from air-gapped computers over cellular frequencies.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] The transmission - generated by a standard internal bus - renders the computer into a small cellular transmitter antenna.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] In general, malware can exploit various hardware combinations to leak sensitive information from air-gapped systems using "air-gap covert channels".
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] These hardware combinations use a number of different media to bridge the air-gap, including: acoustic, light, seismic, magnetic, thermal, and radio-frequency.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] From a security perspective, a major drawback of an air gapped network is the inability of software to automatically self update.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] Users and system administrators must instead download and install updates manually.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] If a strict update routine is not followed, this results in out-of-date software running on the network, which may contain known security vulnerabilities.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] System administrators may manage software updates in an air gapped network using dedicated solutions such as Windows Server Update Services or network logon scripts.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] Such mechanisms would allow all computers on the air gapped network to automatically install updates after the system administrator downloads the updates from the Internet once.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] The problem is not completely eliminated, though, especially if users have administrative privileges on their local workstations and are therefore able to install software that is not centrally managed.
[src:network-segmentation/air-gap-networking] The presence of IoT devices requiring firmware updates can also complicate matters, since often such updates cannot be centrally managed.
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] A **bastion host** is a special-purpose computer on a network specifically designed and configured to withstand attacks, so named by analogy to the bastion, a military fortification.
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] The computer generally hosts a single application or process, for example, a proxy server or load balancer, and all other services are removed or limited to reduce the threat to the computer.
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] It is hardened in this manner primarily due to its location and purpose, which is either on the outside of a firewall or inside of a demilitarized zone (DMZ) and usually involves access from untrusted networks or computers.
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] These computers are also equipped with special networking interfaces to withstand high-bandwidth attacks through the internet.
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] The term is generally attributed to a 1990 article discussing firewalls by Marcus J.
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] Ranum, who defined a bastion host as "a system identified by the firewall administrator as a critical strong point in the network security.
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] Generally, bastion hosts will have some degree of extra attention paid to their security, may undergo regular audits, and may have modified software".
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] It has also been described as "any computer that is fully exposed to attack by being on the public side of the DMZ, unprotected by a firewall or filtering router.
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] Firewalls and routers, anything that provides perimeter access control security can be considered bastion hosts.
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] Other types of bastion hosts can include web, mail, DNS, and FTP servers.
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] Due to their exposure, a great deal of effort must be put into designing and configuring bastion hosts to minimize the chances of penetration".
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] There are two common network configurations that include bastion hosts and their placement.
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] The first requires two firewalls, with bastion hosts sitting between the first "outside world" firewall, and an inside firewall, in a DMZ.
[src:network-segmentation/bastion-host] Often, smaller networks do not have multiple firewalls, so if only one firewall exists in a network, bastion hosts are commonly placed outside the firewall.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] In computer security, a **DMZ** or **demilitarized zone** (sometimes referred to as a **perimeter network** or screened subnet) is a physical or logical subnetwork that contains and exposes an organization's external-facing services to an untrusted, usually larger, network such as the Internet.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The purpose of a DMZ is to add an additional layer of security to an organization's local area network (LAN): an external network node can access only what is exposed in the DMZ, while the rest of the organization's network is protected behind a firewall.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The DMZ functions as a small, isolated network positioned between the Internet and the private network.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] This is not to be confused with a **DMZ host**, a feature present in some home routers that frequently differs greatly from an ordinary DMZ.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The name is from the term *demilitarized zone*, an area between states in which military operations are not permitted.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The DMZ is seen as not belonging to either network bordering it.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] This metaphor applies to the computing use as the DMZ acts as a gateway to the public Internet.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] It is neither as secure as the internal network nor as insecure as the public internet.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] In this case, the hosts most vulnerable to attack are those that provide services to users outside of the local area network, such as e-mail, Web and Domain Name System (DNS) servers.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] Because of the increased potential of these hosts suffering an attack, they are placed into this specific subnetwork in order to protect the rest of the network in case any of them become compromised.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] Hosts in the DMZ are permitted to have only limited connectivity to specific hosts in the internal network, as the content of DMZ is not as secure as the internal network.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] Similarly, communication between hosts in the DMZ and to the external network is also restricted to make the DMZ more secure than the Internet and suitable for housing these special-purpose services.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] This allows hosts in the DMZ to communicate with both the internal and external network, while an intervening firewall controls the traffic between the DMZ servers and the internal network clients, and another firewall would perform some level of control to protect the DMZ from the external network.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] A DMZ configuration provides additional security from external attacks, but it typically has no bearing on internal attacks such as sniffing communication via a packet analyzer or spoofing, such as e-mail spoofing.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] In such architecture, the DMZ usually has the application firewall and the FTP while the CMZ hosts the Web servers.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] Any service that is being provided to users on the external network can be placed in the DMZ.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] Web servers that communicate with an internal database require access to a database server, which may not be publicly accessible and may contain sensitive information.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The web servers can communicate with database servers either directly or through an application firewall for security reasons.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] E-mail messages and particularly the user database are confidential, so they are typically stored on servers that cannot be accessed from the Internet (at least not in an insecure manner), but can be accessed from email servers that are exposed to the Internet.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The mail server inside the DMZ passes incoming mail to the secured/internal mail servers.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] For security, compliance with legal standards such as HIPAA, and monitoring reasons, in a business environment, some enterprises install a proxy server within the DMZ.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] A reverse proxy server, like a proxy server, is an intermediary but is used the other way around.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] Instead of providing a service to internal users wanting to access an external network, it provides indirect access for an external network (usually the Internet) to internal resources.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] This is an extra layer of security particularly recommended when internal resources need to be accessed from the outside, but it's worth noting this design still allows remote (and potentially malicious) users to talk to the internal resources with the help of the proxy.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] There are many different ways to design a network with a DMZ.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] Two of the most basic methods are with a single firewall, also known as the three-legged model, and with dual firewalls, also known as back to back.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] These architectures can be expanded to create very complex architectures depending on the network requirements.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] A single firewall with at least 3 network interfaces can be used to create a network architecture containing a DMZ.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The external network is formed from the Internet service provider to the firewall on the first network interface, the internal network is formed from the second network interface, and the DMZ is formed from the third network interface.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The firewall becomes a single point of failure for the network and must be able to handle all of the traffic going to the DMZ as well as the internal network.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The zones are usually marked with colors -for example, purple for LAN, green for DMZ, red for Internet (with often another color used for wireless zones).
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The most secure approach, according to Colton Fralick, is to use two firewalls to create a DMZ.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The first firewall (also called the "front-end" or "perimeter" firewall) must be configured to allow traffic destined to the DMZ only.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The second firewall (also called "back-end" or "internal" firewall) only allows traffic to the DMZ from the internal network.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] This setup is considered more secure since two devices would need to be compromised.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] There is even more protection if the two firewalls are provided by two different vendors, because it makes it less likely that both devices suffer from the same security vulnerabilities.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] For example, a security hole found to exist in one vendor's system is less likely to occur in the other one.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] One of the drawbacks of this architecture is that it's more costly, both to purchase and to manage.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The practice of using different firewalls from different vendors is sometimes described as a component of a "defense in depth" security strategy.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] Some routers have a feature called **DMZ host**.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] This feature could designate one node (PC or other device with an IP address) as a DMZ host.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] The router's firewall exposes all ports on the DMZ host to the external network and hinders no inbound traffic from the outside going to the DMZ host.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] This is a less secure alternative to port forwarding, which only exposes a handful of ports.
[src:network-segmentation/dmz-computing] In all but the first scenario above, the DMZ host feature is used outside a true DMZ configuration.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] In network security, **microsegmentation** is a network security architecture that establishes security zone boundaries at the level of individual workloads within data centers and cloud environments, which allows workloads to be isolated and secured independently.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] Although originally applied to data center networks, microsegmentation is also used in client network environments.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] It uses operating system firewalls to regulate network traffic between segments.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] Rather than relying on routers, network firewalls, or agents, each host firewall performs auditing and enforcement to limit lateral movement between machines.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] The host-agent segmentation approach relies on endpoint-based agents that are centrally managed and provide visibility into data flows, reducing the difficulty of identifying obscure or encrypted communications.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] Host-based agent technology is widely recognized as an effective method for microsegmentation, as compromised devices operate as hosts and can be controlled directly.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] However, this approach requires software to be installed on every host.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] Hypervisor segmentation is a microsegmentation implementation in which all traffic passes through the hypervisor.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] It enables hypervisor-level traffic monitoring, allows existing firewalls to be used, and supports rule migration as instances are created or removed.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] The network segmentation approach builds on existing infrastructure by using tried-and-true techniques such as access control lists (ACLs) for segmentation.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] Microsegmentation helps limit attack propagation by restricting internal network attack paths.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] In Internet of Things (IoT) environments, microsegmentation helps organizations control lateral communication between devices, which is often unmanaged by perimeter-focused security measures.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] Microsegmentation is generally compatible with environments running common operating systems such as Linux, Windows, and macOS, but support is limited for mainframes and other legacy systems.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] During the initial deployment, some applications may not support microsegmentation, and it can result in operational issues.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] Defining policies that meet the requirements of all internal systems can also be difficult.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] Policy development may involve internal trade-offs and extended coordination, making the process time-consuming for some organizations.
[src:network-segmentation/microsegmentation-network-security] To mitigate deployment complexities and manage policy trade-offs, organizations use automation and self-service applications.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] Network access control is a computer networking solution that uses a set of protocols to define and implement a policy that describes how to secure access to network nodes by devices when they initially attempt to access the network.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] A basic form of NAC is the 802.1X standard.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] Network access control aims to do exactly what the name implies—control access to a network with policies, including pre-admission endpoint security policy checks and post-admission controls over where users and devices can go on a network and what they can do.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] When a computer connects to a computer network, it is not permitted to access anything unless it complies with a business defined policy; including anti-virus protection level, system update level and configuration.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] While the computer is being checked by a pre-installed software agent, it can only access resources that can remediate (resolve or update) any issues.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] Once the policy is met, the computer is able to access network resources and the Internet, within the policies defined by the NAC system.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] NAC is mainly used for endpoint health checks, but it is often tied to Role-based Access.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] Access to the network will be given according to the profile of the person and the results of a posture/health check.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] For example, in an enterprise the HR department could access only HR department files if both the role and the endpoint meets anti-virus minimums.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] NAC is an emerging security product category, whose definition is both evolving and controversial.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] There are two prevailing designs in NAC, based on whether policies are enforced before or after end-stations gain access to the network.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] In the former case, called **pre-admission** NAC, end-stations are inspected prior to being allowed on the network.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] A typical use case of pre-admission NAC would be to prevent clients with out-of-date antivirus signatures from talking to sensitive servers.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] Alternatively, **post-admission** NAC makes enforcement decisions based on user actions, after those users have been provided with access to the network.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] The fundamental idea behind NAC is to allow the network to make access control decisions based on intelligence about end-systems, so the manner in which the network is informed about end-systems is a key design decision.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] A key difference among NAC systems is whether they require agent software to report end-system characteristics, or whether they use scanning and network inventory techniques to discern those characteristics remotely.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] As NAC has matured, software developers such as Microsoft have adopted the approach, providing their network access protection (NAP) agent as part of their Windows 7, Vista and XP releases, however, beginning with Windows 10, Microsoft no longer supports NAP.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] There are also NAP compatible agents for Linux and Mac OS X that provide equal intelligence for these operating systems.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] In some out-of-band systems, agents are distributed on end-stations and report information to a central console, which in turn can control switches to enforce policy.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] In contrast the inline solutions can be single-box solutions which act as internal firewalls for access-layer networks and enforce the policy.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] Out-of-band solutions have the advantage of reusing existing infrastructure; inline products can be easier to deploy on new networks, and may provide more advanced network enforcement capabilities, because they are directly in control of individual packets on the wire.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] However, there are products that are agentless, and have both the inherent advantages of easier, less risky out-of-band deployment, but use techniques to provide inline effectiveness for non-compliant devices, where enforcement is required.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] Network operators deploy NAC products with the expectation that some legitimate clients will be denied access to the network (if users never had out-of-date patch levels, NAC would be unnecessary).
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] Because of this, NAC solutions require a mechanism to remediate the end-user problems that deny them access.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] A quarantine network is a restricted IP network that provides users with routed access only to certain hosts and applications.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] assignment; when a NAC product determines that an end-user is out-of-date, their switch port is assigned to a VLAN that is routed only to patch and update servers, not to the rest of the network.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] (NDP)) for quarantine, avoiding the overhead of managing quarantine VLANs.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] that provides instructions and tools for updating their computer.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] Until their computer passes automated inspection, no network usage besides the captive portal is allowed.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] This is similar to the way paid wireless access works at public access points.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] External Captive Portals allow organizations to offload wireless controllers and switches from hosting web portals.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] A single external portal hosted by a NAC appliance for wireless and wired authentication eliminates the need to create multiple portals, and consolidates policy management processes.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] Using NAC in a mobile deployment, where workers connect over various wireless networks throughout the workday, involves challenges that are not present in a wired LAN environment.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] When a user is denied access because of a security concern, productive use of the device is lost, which can impact the ability to complete a job or serve a customer.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] In addition, automated remediation that takes only seconds on a wired connection may take minutes over a slower wireless data connection, bogging down the device.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] A mobile NAC solution gives system administrators greater control over whether, when and how to remediate the security concern.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] A lower-grade concern such as out-of-date antivirus signatures may result in a simple warning to the user, while more serious issues may result in quarantining the device.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] Policies may be set so that automated remediation, such as pushing out and applying security patches and updates, is withheld until the device is connected over a Wi-Fi or faster connection, or after working hours.
[src:network-segmentation/network-access-control] This allows administrators to most appropriately balance the need for security against the goal of keeping workers productive.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] Network segmentation is the core of multi-layer defense in depth for modern services.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] The main goal of this cheat sheet is to show the basics of network segmentation to effectively counter attacks by building a secure and maximally isolated service network architecture.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] (BACKEND) The following example shows an organization's local network.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] Usually some information systems of the company interact with each other.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] It is important to define a firewall policy for such interactions.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] The base allowed interactions are indicated by the green arrows in the image below: (Interservice interaction) The image above also shows the allowed access from the FRONTEND and MIDDLEWARE segments to external networks (the Internet, for example).
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] Access from the MIDDLEWARE segment to the BACKEND segment of another service is prohibited (access to a foreign database bypassing the application server is prohibited).
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] If you prefer to have fewer networks in your organization and host more applications on each network, it is acceptable to host the load balancer on those networks.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] This balancer will balance traffic to applications on the network.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] In this case, it will be necessary to open one port to such a network, and balancing will be performed, for example, based on the HTTP request parameters.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] As you can see, there is only one incoming access to each network, access is opened up to the balancer in the network.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] However, in this case, segmentation no longer works, access control between applications from different network segments is performed at the 7th level of the OSI model using a balancer.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] The organization must define a "paper" policy that describes firewall rules and basic allowed network access.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] It is convenient when the policy is described by similar images.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] The information is presented as concisely and simply as possible.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] Examples in the network policy will help colleagues quickly understand what access is potentially allowed and can be requested.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] The network security policy may define, for example, the basic permissions allowed for the software development system.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] It is important that in the event of a compromise of any information system, its logs are not subsequently modified by an attacker.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] To do this, you can do the following: copy the logs to a separate server, for example, using the syslog protocol, which does not allow an attacker to modify the logs, syslog only allows you to add new events to the logs.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] The network security policy for this activity looks like this: (Logging) In this example, we are also talking about application logs that may contain security events, as well as potentially important events that may indicate an attack.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation-cheat-sheet] Suppose a company uses Zabbix as an IT monitoring system.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation] When a cyber-criminal gains unauthorized access to a network, segmentation or “zoning” can provide effective controls to limit further movement across the network.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation] For example separating the network for Payment Card authorizations from those for Point-of-Service (till) or customer Wi-Fi traffic.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation] A sound security policy entails segmenting the network into multiple zones, with varying security requirements, and rigorously enforcing the policy on what is allowed to move from zone to zone.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation] Finance and Human Resources typically need access via their own VLAN to their application servers because of the confidential nature of the information they process and store.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation] Other groups of personnel may require their own segregated networks, such as server administrators, security administration, managers and executives.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation] Third parties are usually required to have their own segments, with different administration passwords to the main network, to avoid attacks via a compromised, less well protected, third party site.
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation] Segregation is typically achieved by a combination of firewalls and VLANs (virtual local area networks).
[src:network-segmentation/network-segmentation] Software-defined networking (SDN) can allow the creation and management of micro-segmented networks.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] A **virtual local area network** (**VLAN**) is a local area network broadcast domain that is partitioned and isolated in a virtual network at the data link layer (OSI layer 2).
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] A VLAN behaves like a virtual network switch or network link that can share the same physical structure with other VLANs while staying logically separate from them.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLANs work by applying tags to network frames that are forwarded within the broadcast domain, creating the appearance and functionality of network traffic that behaves as if it were split between separate networks.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] In this way, VLANs can keep network applications separate despite being connected to the same physical network, and without requiring multiple sets of cabling and networking devices to be deployed.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLANs allow network administrators to group hosts together even if the hosts are not directly connected to the same network switch.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Because VLAN membership can be configured through software, this can greatly simplify network design and deployment.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Without VLANs, grouping hosts according to their resources requires relocating nodes or rewiring data links.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLANs allow devices that must be kept separate to share the cabling of a physical network and yet be prevented from directly interacting with one another.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] This managed sharing yields gains in simplicity, security, traffic control, and economy.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Many Internet hosting services use VLANs to separate customers' private zones from one another, enabling each customer's servers to be grouped within a single network segment regardless of where the individual servers are located in the data center.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Some precautions are needed to prevent traffic "escaping" from a given VLAN, an exploit known as VLAN hopping.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] To subdivide a network into VLANs, one configures network equipment.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Simpler equipment might partition only each physical port, in which case each VLAN runs over a dedicated network cable.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] More sophisticated devices can mark frames through VLAN tagging, so that a single interconnect (*trunk*) may be used to transport data for multiple VLANs.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Since VLANs share bandwidth, a VLAN trunk can use link aggregation, quality-of-service prioritization, or both to route data efficiently.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLANs address issues such as scalability, security, and network management.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Network architects set up VLANs to provide network segmentation.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Routers between VLANs filter broadcast traffic, enhance network security, perform address summarization, and mitigate network congestion.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] In a network utilizing broadcasts for service discovery, address assignment and resolution and other services, as the number of peers on a network grows, the frequency of broadcasts also increases.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLANs can help manage broadcast traffic by forming multiple broadcast domains.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Breaking up a large network into smaller independent segments reduces the amount of broadcast traffic each network device and network segment has to bear.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Switches may not bridge network traffic between VLANs, as doing so would violate the integrity of the VLAN broadcast domain.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLANs can also help create multiple layer 3 networks on a single physical infrastructure.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLANs are data link layer (OSI layer 2) constructs, analogous to Internet Protocol (IP) subnets, which are network layer (OSI layer 3) constructs.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] In an environment employing VLANs, a one-to-one relationship often exists between VLANs and IP subnets, although it is possible to have multiple subnets on one VLAN.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Without VLAN capability, users are assigned to networks based on geography and are limited by physical topologies and distances.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLANs can logically group networks to decouple the users' network location from their physical location.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] By using VLANs, one can control traffic patterns and react quickly to employee or equipment relocations.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLANs provide the flexibility to adapt to changes in network requirements and allow for simplified administration.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] A common infrastructure shared across VLAN trunks can provide a measure of security with great flexibility for a comparatively low cost.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Quality of service schemes can optimize traffic on trunk links for real-time (e.g.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] However, VLANs as a security solution should be implemented with great care as they can be defeated unless implemented carefully.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] In cloud computing VLANs, IP addresses, and MAC addresses in the cloud are resources that end users can manage.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] To help mitigate security issues, placing cloud-based virtual machines on VLANs may be preferable to placing them directly on the Internet.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] After successful experiments with voice over Ethernet from 1981 to 1984, W.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] David Sincoskie joined Bellcore and began addressing the problem of scaling up Ethernet networks.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] At 10 Mbit/s, Ethernet was faster than most alternatives at the time.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] However, Ethernet was a broadcast network and there was no good way of connecting multiple Ethernet networks together.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] This limited the total bandwidth of an Ethernet network to 10 Mbit/s and the maximum distance between nodes to a few hundred feet.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] By contrast, although the existing telephone network's speed for individual connections was limited to 56 kbit/s (less than one hundredth of Ethernet's speed), the total bandwidth of that network was estimated at 1 Tbit/s (100,000 times greater than Ethernet).
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Although it was possible to use IP routing to connect multiple Ethernet networks together, it was expensive and relatively slow.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Sincoskie started looking for alternatives that required less processing per packet.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] In the process, he independently reinvented transparent bridging, the technique used in modern Ethernet switches.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] However, using switches to connect multiple Ethernet networks in a fault-tolerant fashion requires redundant paths through that network, which in turn requires a spanning tree configuration.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] This ensures that there is only one *active* path from any source node to any destination on the network.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] This causes centrally located switches to become bottlenecks, limiting scalability as more networks are interconnected.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] To help alleviate this problem, Sincoskie invented VLANs by adding a tag (an individual label, such as A, B, C, and so on) to each Ethernet frame.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] In this scheme, each switch could be assigned to handle frames of a specific tag and ignore the rest.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] The networks could be interconnected with three spanning trees, one for each color.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] By sending a mix of different frame tags, the aggregate bandwidth could be improved.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Sincoskie referred to this as a *multitree bridge*.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] He and Chase Cotton created and refined the algorithms necessary to make the system feasible.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] This *color* is what is now known in the Ethernet frame as the IEEE 802.1Q header, or the VLAN tag.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] While VLANs are commonly used in modern Ethernet networks, they are not used in the manner first envisioned here.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] In 1998, Ethernet VLANs were described in the first edition of the IEEE 802.1Q-1998 standard.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] This was extended with IEEE 802.1ad to allow nested VLAN tags in service of provider bridging.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] This mechanism was improved with IEEE 802.1ah-2008.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Early network designers often segmented physical LANs with the aim of reducing the size of the Ethernet collision domain—thus improving performance.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] When Ethernet switches made this a non-issue (because each switch port is a collision domain), attention turned to reducing the size of the data link layer broadcast domain.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLANs were first employed to separate several broadcast domains across one physical medium.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] A VLAN can also serve to restrict access to network resources without regard to physical topology of the network.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLANs operate at the data link layer of the OSI model.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Administrators often configure a VLAN to map directly to an IP network, or subnet, which gives the appearance of involving the network layer.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Generally, VLANs within the same organization will be assigned different non-overlapping network address ranges.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] There is no issue with separate VLANs using identical overlapping address ranges (e.g. two VLANs each use the private network *192.168.0.0/16*).
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] However, it is not possible to route data between two networks with overlapping addresses without delicate IP remapping, so if the goal of VLANs is segmentation of a larger overall organizational network, non-overlapping addresses must be used in each separate VLAN.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] A basic switch that is not configured for VLANs has VLAN functionality disabled or permanently enabled with a *default VLAN* that contains all ports on the device as members.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] The default VLAN typically uses VLAN identifier 1.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Every device connected to one of its ports can send packets to any of the others.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Separating ports by VLAN groups separates their traffic very much like connecting each group using a distinct switch for each group.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Remote management of the switch requires that the administrative functions be associated with one or more of the configured VLANs.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] In the context of VLANs, the term *trunk* denotes a network link carrying multiple VLANs, which are identified by labels (or *tags*) inserted into their packets.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Such trunks must run between *tagged ports* of VLAN-aware devices, so they are often switch-to-switch or switch-to-router links rather than links to hosts.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] (Note that the term 'trunk' is also used for what Cisco calls "channels" : Link Aggregation or Port Trunking).
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] A router (Layer 3 device) serves as the backbone for network traffic going across different VLANs.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] It is only when the VLAN port group is to extend to another device that tagging is used.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Since communications between ports on two different switches travel via the uplink ports of each switch involved, every VLAN containing such ports must also contain the uplink port of each switch involved, and traffic through these ports must be tagged.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Switches typically have no built-in method to indicate VLAN to port associations to someone working in a wiring closet.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] It is necessary for a technician to either have administrative access to the device to view its configuration, or for VLAN port assignment charts or diagrams to be kept next to the switches in each wiring closet.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] The protocol most commonly used today to support VLANs is IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] The IEEE 802.1 working group defined this method of multiplexing VLANs in an effort to provide multivendor VLAN support.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Prior to the introduction of the 802.1Q standard, several proprietary protocols existed, such as Cisco Inter-Switch Link (ISL) and 3Com's Virtual LAN Trunk (VLT).
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Cisco also implemented VLANs over FDDI by carrying VLAN information in an IEEE 802.10 frame header, contrary to the purpose of the IEEE 802.10 standard.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Both ISL and IEEE 802.1Q perform *explicit tagging* – the frame itself is tagged with VLAN identifiers.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] ISL uses an external tagging process that does not modify the Ethernet frame, while 802.1Q uses a frame-internal field for tagging, and therefore does modify the basic Ethernet frame structure.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] This internal tagging allows IEEE 802.1Q to work on both access and trunk links using standard Ethernet hardware.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Under IEEE 802.1Q, the maximum number of VLANs on a given Ethernet network is 4,094 (4,096 values provided by the 12-bit VID field minus reserved values at each end of the range, 0 and 4,095).
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] This does not impose the same limit on the number of IP subnets in such a network since a single VLAN can contain multiple IP subnets.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] IEEE 802.1ad extends the number of VLANs supported by adding support for multiple, nested VLAN tags.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] IEEE 802.1aq (Shortest Path Bridging) expands the VLAN limit to 16 million.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Both improvements have been incorporated into the IEEE 802.1Q standard.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Inter-Switch Link (ISL) is a Cisco proprietary protocol used to interconnect switches and maintain VLAN information as traffic travels between switches on trunk links.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] ISL is provided as an alternative to IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] ISL is available only on some Cisco equipment and has been deprecated.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLAN Trunking Protocol (VTP) is a Cisco proprietary protocol that propagates the definition of VLANs on the whole local area network.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VTP is available on most of the Cisco Catalyst Family products.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] The comparable IEEE standard in use by other manufacturers is GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP) or the more recent Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP).
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol is an application of Multiple Registration Protocol that allows automatic configuration of VLAN information on network switches.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Specifically, it provides a method to dynamically share VLAN information and configure the needed VLANs.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLAN membership can be established either statically or dynamically.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Static VLANs are also referred to as port-based VLANs.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Static VLAN assignments are created by assigning ports to a VLAN.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] As a device enters the network, the device automatically assumes the VLAN of the port.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] If the user changes ports and needs access to the same VLAN, the network administrator must manually make a port-to-VLAN assignment for the new connection.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Dynamic VLANs are created using software or by protocol.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] With a VLAN Management Policy Server (VMPS), an administrator can assign switch ports to VLANs dynamically based on information such as the source MAC address of the device connected to the port or the username used to log onto that device.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] As a device enters the network, the switch queries a database for the VLAN membership of the port that device is connected to.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Protocol methods include Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP) and the somewhat obsolete GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP).
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] In a switch that supports protocol-based VLANs, traffic may be handled on the basis of its protocol.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] Essentially, this segregates or forwards traffic from a port depending on the particular protocol of that traffic; traffic of any other protocol is not forwarded on the port.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] This allows, for example, IP and IPX traffic to be automatically segregated by the network.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] VLAN cross connect (CC or VLAN-XC) is a mechanism used to create Switched VLANs, VLAN CC uses IEEE 802.1ad frames where the S Tag is used as a Label as in MPLS.
[src:network-segmentation/virtual-lan] IEEE approves the use of such a mechanism in part 6.11 of IEEE 802.1ad-2005.
